  '13': {
    green: [
      { q: 'State the phenomenon of electromagnetic induction.', marks: 2, tier: 'green',
        modelAnswer: `When a conductor experiences a change in magnetic flux (for example, by moving relative to a magnetic field or by the field changing around it), a potential difference (EMF) is induced across its ends. If the conductor is part of a complete circuit, a current flows.` },
      { q: 'State two ways of increasing the induced EMF in a generator.', marks: 2, tier: 'green',
        modelAnswer: `Any two of:\n• Increase the speed of rotation (more flux changes per second).\n• Use a stronger magnetic field.\n• Increase the number of turns on the coil.\n• Use a soft iron core / increase the cross-sectional area of the coil.` },
      { q: 'State what a transformer does and why it is important.', marks: 2, tier: 'green',
        modelAnswer: `A transformer changes the voltage of an alternating supply. It is essential in the National Grid for stepping voltage up for efficient long-distance transmission and stepping it down for safe use. It requires AC because it works by induction from a changing magnetic flux.` },
      { q: 'State the transformer equation relating turns and voltages.', marks: 2, tier: 'green',
        modelAnswer: `V_s / V_p = N_s / N_p (secondary voltage ÷ primary voltage = secondary turns ÷ primary turns). For an ideal transformer, V_p × I_p = V_s × I_s (power conservation).` },
    ],
    amber: [
      { q: 'Explain why a transformer cannot work with a steady DC supply.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `A transformer works by the changing magnetic flux from the primary coil inducing a changing EMF in the secondary coil. Direct current produces a steady magnetic flux that does not change with time, so no EMF is induced in the secondary coil. (Only a brief pulse is induced the moment the DC is switched on or off.) Transformers therefore require AC (or a pulsed DC) for continuous operation.` },
      { q: 'A step-up transformer has 500 turns on its primary coil and 5000 on its secondary coil. The primary voltage is 230 V. Calculate the secondary voltage and, if the primary current is 20 A, the ideal secondary current.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `V_s = V_p × (N_s / N_p) = 230 × 5000/500 = 2300 V.\nIdeal: V_p I_p = V_s I_s → I_s = 230 × 20 / 2300 = 2.0 A.` },
      { q: 'Describe how a simple AC generator (alternator) works.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `A coil rotates inside a magnetic field, cutting field lines. An EMF is induced across the coil (electromagnetic induction). The coil is connected to the external circuit through two slip rings and brushes, so the coil\'s two ends always connect to the same external terminals. As the coil rotates, the induced EMF swings positive, zero, negative, zero... once per revolution — an alternating voltage. A filament lamp connected across the output would flicker (or hum) at twice the rotation frequency.` },
      { q: 'Explain why eddy currents can cause losses in a transformer and how they can be reduced.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `The changing magnetic flux in the core induces swirling currents ("eddy currents") in the core itself. These currents heat the core, dissipating energy and reducing efficiency. To reduce them, cores are made from thin sheets of iron insulated from each other (a laminated core). This keeps the core magnetically continuous but electrically broken into thin layers so eddy currents can only flow in small loops, greatly reducing energy loss.` },
    ],
    red: [
      { q: 'A transmission line carries a power of 1 MW. Calculate the current at 400 V and at 400 kV, and explain the significance for I²R losses.', marks: 5, tier: 'red',
        modelAnswer: `At 400 V: I = P / V = 1 × 10⁶ / 400 = 2500 A.\nAt 400 kV: I = 1 × 10⁶ / 400 × 10³ = 2.5 A.\nPower dissipated in cables P_loss = I²R. At 400 V losses scale with 2500² = 6.25 × 10⁶; at 400 kV with 2.5² = 6.25. That\'s a factor of 10⁶ difference — a million times smaller loss for the same cable resistance. This is why the National Grid uses step-up transformers to very high voltages for transmission and step-down transformers near towns.` },
      { q: 'Evaluate the claim: "Transformers turn a small input power into a large output power."', marks: 5, tier: 'red',
        modelAnswer: `The claim is incorrect. A transformer changes voltage and current but, by conservation of energy, cannot create energy. In an ideal transformer, input power equals output power (V_p I_p = V_s I_s). A step-up transformer increases voltage but decreases current in the same ratio, so output power is equal (ideal) or slightly less (real). Real transformers lose some energy as heat in the coils (I²R) and core (eddy currents / hysteresis), making output power slightly less than input. So transformers are very efficient energy-converters but never amplifiers of power — they only redistribute it between V and I.` },
    ],
  },

